I have found (using perl scripts) that to call the cleartool executable directly from a shell is much slower than using the Clearcase COM object. Performance is much faster, although the interpretation of the output is a little more difficult (line breaks, etc)

e.g. 
my $ct = Win32::OLE->new('ClearCase.ClearTool') or die "Could not create ClearTool object\n"; 
$direct = $ct->CmdExec("lsvob -short -host $COMPUTER");

Go to Source > repo (select any branches directory) > Reports > Code Metrics, you would get 
{noformat}
No LOC data (by extension) found at <repo/branches/directory> - has the repository finished indexing?
{noformat}

An incorrect VOB path is used to retrieve the type manager in Base ClearCase environments that reuse an existing snapshot view whose load rules are configured to process a subdirectory of a VOB.  The error generated is:

{code}
2010-05-06 10:01:36,209 WARN  [btpool0-114] fisheye.app ClearCaseContext-handleProcessError - Error executing command (cleartool lstype -l eltype:text_file@/vob/insight/insightgui ) :  cleartool: Error: Unable to determine VOB for pathname "/vob/insight/insightgui".
{code}

This problem only occurs when the FishEye repository is configured to reuse an existing snapshot view, and the load rules for the snapshot view include a VOB subpath reference (eg. /vob/insight/insightgui) instead of the actual VOB location (eg. /vob/insight). 

FishEye is assuming that the path specified in the load rule is the VOB location, and uses this value when it tries to perform an operation to find the type manager for a file type.

If you create a symlink directly to the fisheyectl.sh script it won't find the fisheyeboot.jar because it real path won't be resolved  correctly. We currently jsut use the script name: 

{code}PRG=$0{code}

A dodgy hack would be to do something like:

{code}PRG=`ls -l $0 | awk '{print $NF}'`{code}

Which will resolve the full path.
